\begin{Shaded}

\item
  (2 Points) Create two plots (using function \texttt{plot} with option
  \texttt{type="l"}) showing (1) how the mean (\emph{i.e.,} expected
  value) of \(W^2\) over 1000 samples of size \(n\) changes with
  increasing sample size (vary \(n\) from 1 to 100), for data sampled
  from a standard normal distribution, and (2) how the mean
  (\emph{i.e.,} expected) sample variance changes with increasing sample
  size for the same distribution (using function \texttt{var}).
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Problem 2.2 (10 Points)}\label{problem-2.2-10-points}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\Alph{enumi}.}
\item
  (2 Points) Write a function to calculate the \textbf{likelihood} for a
  single observation \(y_i\) of body mass that takes \(y_i\), \(\mu_1\),
  \(\mu_2\), \(\sigma_1\), \(\sigma_2\), and \(p\) as inputs. Because of
  what we will be doing later on in this question, we want our function
  to take our parameters as a single vector with named entries
  \texttt{mu1}, \texttt{mu1}, \texttt{sd1}, \texttt{sd2}, and \texttt{p}
  so that you can reference them with \texttt{parameters{[}"mu1"{]}}
  (and similar). Your function should take the following general form

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{params }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"mu1"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"mu2"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"sd1"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"sd2"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"p"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{likelihoodSingleObservation }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(params,yi)\{}

\NormalTok{  yi\_likelihood }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ ((params[}\StringTok{"p"}\NormalTok{] }\SpecialCharTok{*} \FunctionTok{dnorm}\NormalTok{(yi, params[}\StringTok{"mu1"}\NormalTok{], params[}\StringTok{"sd1"}\NormalTok{])) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ ((}\DecValTok{1} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ params[}\StringTok{"p"}\NormalTok{]) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \FunctionTok{dnorm}\NormalTok{(yi, params[}\StringTok{"mu2"}\NormalTok{], params[}\StringTok{"sd2"}\NormalTok{])))}

  \FunctionTok{return}\NormalTok{(yi\_likelihood)}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\item
  (2 Points) Write a function to calculate the \textbf{log likelihood}
  for a vector of observations \(y=\{y_1,y_2,...,y_n\}\) and given
  parameter vector \texttt{parameters}. This function will need to call
  the function you wrote in Part A (yes, you can call a function inside
  of another function). Your function should take the following general
  form:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{y }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{()}

\NormalTok{likelihoodAllObservations }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(params,y)\{}

  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{(params[}\StringTok{"p"}\NormalTok{] }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}} \DecValTok{0} \SpecialCharTok{|} 
\NormalTok{     params[}\StringTok{"p"}\NormalTok{] }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{1} \SpecialCharTok{|} 
\NormalTok{     params[}\StringTok{"sd1"}\NormalTok{] }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}} \DecValTok{0} \SpecialCharTok{|} 
\NormalTok{     params[}\StringTok{"sd2"}\NormalTok{] }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)\{}
    \FunctionTok{return}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\ConstantTok{Inf}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  \} }\ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{ \{}

\NormalTok{    y\_log\_likelihood }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{likelihoodSingleObservation}\NormalTok{(params, y)))}

    \FunctionTok{return}\NormalTok{(y\_log\_likelihood)}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\item
  (0 Points) Now we want to use this function to fit parameters to our
  penguin data. Unlike in Problem 2.1, just plotting the likelihoods
  won't work because we are dealing with so many parameters here.
  Instead we will use a function for numerical optimization that will
  search possible parameter combinations, score them using our
  likelihood function and data, and then return the best result. Run the

\begin{Shaded}

\item
  (2 Points) Now, we want to be able to, in a principled way, assign
  individual Penguins to our two groups. This is a common problem when
  clustering data, and our Gaussian Mixture model is essentially an
  approach for performing such clustering. What we want is the
  ``posterior predictive probability'' that penguin belongs to
  distribution 1 (or, one minus that probability that is belongs to
  distribution 2). The word ``posterior'' means it comes after
  incorporating information from the original data, and ``predictive''
  because we want to predict group membership. We can write this
  probability as:

  \[P(y\text{ from }X_1|y,\text{ parameters})=\frac{pf(y|\mu_1,\sigma_1)}{pf(y|\mu_1,\sigma_1)+(1-p)f(y|\mu_2,\sigma_2)}\]

  Write a function to calculate this probability, apply it to your
  penguin data using your parameter estimates from Part C, and then plot
  two histograms depicting the distribution of this probability for the
  two penguin species (Adelie and Gentoo) in your dataset. Note that the
  denominator in this equation is just the output of the function your
  wrote in Part A.
\end{enumerate}
